  "forceAction_usage_note": "ContinuousMotionExplorer._teleport calls controller.step(action='Teleport', position={x, y, z}, ..., forceAction=True) at src/env/continuous_motion_explorer.py:426. `git blame` shows forceAction=True has been in the production explorer since the session-4 commit ec172c7 that introduced the ContinuousMotionExplorer class \u2014 it is NOT a session-5 leak from pose-search reachability testing; the pose-search and motion-continuity scripts introduced this session independently set forceAction=True, but the production path predates them. forceAction=True bypasses AI2-THOR's NavMesh + floor-snap validation. Combined with the input position dict's y value coming from two different sources \u2014 route.json's viewing_position.y = 0.9009998 (eye-height snapshot from the prior repo's stage_0b setup) for close-up steps; NavMesh-planned waypoints with y \u2248 0.006 (floor level) for transit steps \u2014 the agent's BASE y oscillates between 0.901 (close-up) and 0.006 (transit) at every close_up\u2194transit phase boundary. With the camera offset fixed above the base, the rendered camera elevation oscillates by ~0.9m, producing the bobbing the reviewer observed in v2 calibration frames. No horizontal wall-jump was found: the [0.25, 0.50) and [1.0, 2.0) displacement bins are empty (zero pairs); the reviewer's 'agent jumps through walls' observation is the visual effect of the y-bob \u2014 the camera leaping ~0.9m in elevation in a single rendered frame at every close_up\u2194transit transition.",
  "root_cause_summary": {
    "bug": "Agent base y oscillates between close-up steps (y = 0.901, eye-height from route.json) and transit steps (y = 0.006, NavMesh floor).",
    "mechanism": "ContinuousMotionExplorer._teleport copies position.y from the input dict and passes it to AI2-THOR's Teleport with forceAction=True. forceAction bypasses the floor-snap validation, so the agent base lands at whatever y is specified rather than being snapped to the NavMesh floor.",
    "introduced": "Session-4 commit ec172c7 (the ContinuousMotionExplorer's initial implementation). All v1 and v2 calibrations + the aborted Phase 2 collection ran with this bug present; rendered frames had a ~1.8m camera elevation during close-up segments and a ~0.9m camera elevation during transit segments.",
    "rendered_camera_elevation_close_up_m": 1.801,
    "rendered_camera_elevation_transit_m": 0.906,
    "elevation_delta_m": 0.894,
    "recommended_fix": "In `_teleport`, drop the input position dict's y value; always use the NavMesh floor y (queried once at init via controller.step('GetReachablePositions') and stored on the explorer as self._agent_floor_y). Optionally add `standing=True` to the Teleport call to make the agent's standing posture explicit. forceAction=True can be retained \u2014 it is required for the close-up path's off-grid 0.20m steps (which don't align to AI2-THOR's 0.25m grid). The fix is ~5 lines in ContinuousMotionExplorer plus a query at __init__ time.",
    "downstream_invalidation": "All v1 (session-4) and v2 (session-5) calibration data, the session-5 preflight runs, the pose-search candidate frames, the motion-continuity sweep frames, and the aborted Phase 2 collection (6800 frames) were rendered with the camera-bobbing bug present. Within-phase-pair analyses (close_up\u2192close_up, transit\u2192transit) are unaffected because y is constant within each phase; cross-phase analyses and the bird's-eye close-up framing of every prior rendered frame are. Re-doing v2 calibration + preflight after the fix is required; the pose-search verdict on DT_h118 should be re-verified at the corrected camera height; the \u00a78.4 absolute and differential gate thresholds may need recalibration once the encoder sees correctly-rendered Stage A/B apex frames."
  }
